 usual recommendation of group living. Schutt’s findings challenge the assumptions behind current policy and call for reexamining housing programs for this population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGroup homes for people with mental disabilities -- United States. 0aGroup homes for people with mental disabilitieszUnited States. 0aMentally ill homeless persons -- United States. 0aMentally ill homeless personszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh1 aGoldfinger, Stephen M, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSeidman, Larry J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674058880zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674058880423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674058880/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK